{"sections":[],"abstract":[{"text":"The case for replacing stringly-typed SFSymbol names with compiler-checked properties.","type":"text"}],"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"anchor":"Overview","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Every SFSymbol reference in an Apple-platform app passes through a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"String"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"code":["Image(systemName: \"square.and.arrow.up\")","let icon = UIImage(systemName: \"gear\")"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"That string is never validated by the compiler. Three consequences follow, and all of them are maintenance costs that compound over the life of a codebase."}]},{"anchor":"No-autocomplete","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"No autocomplete"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Xcode can’t suggest symbol names, because they aren’t part of your program — they’re opaque keys resolved at runtime. You context-switch to the SFSymbols app, search, copy, paste."}]},{"anchor":"No-compile-time-check","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"No compile-time check"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"\"gear\"","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" (valid) and "},{"code":"\"gears\"","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" (not a symbol) are both just "},{"code":"String","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":". The type system has nothing to verify against, so a typo is not a build error."}]},{"anchor":"Silent-runtime-failure","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"Silent runtime failure"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"UIImage(systemName:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" returns "},{"code":"nil","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" for an unknown name; "},{"code":"Image(systemName:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" renders nothing. Neither throws. The bug ships, and the only signal is “the button looks wrong.”"}]},{"text":"The fix","type":"heading","anchor":"The-fix","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"SFSymbolsKit makes the catalog ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"data in your program","type":"text"}]},{"text":": a typed property per symbol, generated from Apple’s list. Autocomplete works, typos are compile errors, refactors are safe, and the whole catalog becomes enumerable.","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["Image(systemName: String.SFSymbols.squareAndArrowUp)   \/\/ can't be misspelled"]}],"kind":"content"}],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/sfsymbolskit\/typesafesymbols"]}],"seeAlsoSections":[{"anchor":"Related-Documentation","identifiers":["doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit\/ChoosingAnAPI","doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit\/ForAIAgents"],"title":"Related Documentation"},{"anchor":"Essentials","generated":true,"title":"Essentials","identifiers":["doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit\/ChoosingAnAPI"]}],"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit\/TypeSafeSymbols"},"kind":"article","hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit"]]},"schemaVersion":{"minor":3,"patch":0,"major":0},"metadata":{"title":"Why Type-Safe Symbols","role":"article","roleHeading":"Article","modules":[{"name":"SFSymbolsKit"}]},"references":{"doc://com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit/documentation/SFSymbolsKit/ForAIAgents":{"type":"topic","kind":"article","abstract":[{"text":"Why SFSymbolsKit specifically solves a problem that AI coding assistants have with SFSymbols — and how an agent should use it.","type":"text"}],"title":"SFSymbolsKit for AI Coding Agents","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit\/ForAIAgents","url":"\/documentation\/sfsymbolskit\/foraiagents","role":"article"},"doc://com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit/documentation/SFSymbolsKit":{"type":"topic","abstract":[{"text":"Apple’s entire SFSymbols catalog as a strongly-typed Swift API — autocompleted, refactor-safe, and compile-checked.","type":"text"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit","kind":"symbol","title":"SFSymbolsKit","url":"\/documentation\/sfsymbolskit","role":"collection"},"doc://com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit/documentation/SFSymbolsKit/ChoosingAnAPI":{"type":"topic","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"SFSymbolsKit exposes the same catalog through four surfaces. Pick the one that matches the layer you’re working at."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit\/ChoosingAnAPI","kind":"article","title":"Choosing an API","url":"\/documentation\/sfsymbolskit\/choosinganapi","role":"article"}}}